result.execSummary:
The defendant Joshua J. Feller was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by a risk and needs assessment and the probation agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions. 

55 days jail credit, if revoked.

You shall have no contact, directly or indirectly, either personally, by mail, telephone or through any other person, or by any other means with the Black River Memorial Hospital, except for emergency purposes.

You must submit to and successfully complete a mental health evaluation to determine appropriate programming commensurate with needs identified.  Must comply with all recommendations.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions.

If probation is revoked and a prison term is not ordered, or if probation is discharged or terminated, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant in favor of any restitution victims and government entities for outstanding financial obligations.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt. Must pay all costs of supervision and court ordered financial obligations during the term of probation. 

Court advised defendant of the DNA submission requirement.

1:30 PM Defendant Joshua J. Feller in court.  Attorney Tsz-King Tse appeared by video for Joshua J. Feller.  Attorney Crystal Leigh Jensen in court for State of Wisconsin. State in compliance with victim rights. Defendant enters a plea of Guilty to Count 1 and 3. State/s offer is with the weapons enhancer. Defendant questions that. Court room cleared except for defendant and attorney by video to discuss. Proceeding with use of a dangerous weapon as an enhancer. 
Court reviewed the elements and potential penalties of the charge the defendant plead to.  He understood.   Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant. He understood. Defense stipulated that there is a factual basis for the plea.   Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily, knowingly and intelligently entered his/her plea and waived his constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty of Disorderly Conduct contrary to 947.01(1) 939.63.(1)(a), Resisting or Obstructing an Officer contrary to 946.41(1). Count 2 DRI. Defendant exercised his right to allocution. 

Joint recommendation: Withhold sentence, 18 months probation. Conditions: mental health evaluation, no contact with Black River Memorial Hospital, except for emergency purposes. Risk and needs assessment, follow through. 55 days credit.  

Court adopts the joint recommendation: Withholds sentence, orders 18 months probation, complete a mental health evaluation follow through with any programing agents deems necessary. No contact with Black River Memorial Hospital, except for emergency purposes. Risk and needs assessment, follow through. 55 days jail credit, if revoked. Court costs, pay through probation. 

The defendant is ORDERED  to report to the Jackson County Jail to submit the required DNA specimen. Contact the Jackson County Sheriff's Department at 715-284-5357 to arrange for an appointment.
